  ],
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are the 8 B vitamins in a B complex?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'A complete B complex contains all 8 essential B vitamins: B1 (thiamine) for energy metabolism, B2 (riboflavin) for cellular energy and antioxidant function, B3 (niacin) for DNA repair and cholesterol metabolism, B5 (pantothenic acid) for hormone and neurotransmitter synthesis, B6 (pyridoxine) for amino acid metabolism and brain development, B7 (biotin) for hair, skin, and nail health, B9 (folate) for DNA synthesis and cell division, and B12 (cobalamin) for nerve function and red blood cell formation. Each plays a unique role, but they work synergistically — supplementing all 8 together ensures optimal function of the entire B-vitamin pathway.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why are methylated B vitamins better?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Methylated B vitamins (methylfolate for B9, methylcobalamin for B12) are the bioactive forms that your body can use immediately without additional enzymatic conversion. Approximately 30-40% of the population carries the MTHFR gene variant, which impairs the ability to convert synthetic folic acid into active methylfolate. For these individuals, synthetic folic acid provides little to no benefit. Similarly, methylcobalamin (active B12) bypasses the conversion step required by cyanocobalamin (synthetic B12). Choosing methylated forms ensures that the supplement works for everyone, regardless of genetic variations in methylation capacity.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are the signs of B vitamin deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'B vitamin deficiency symptoms vary by specific vitamin but commonly include: persistent fatigue and low energy (B12, B6, folate), brain fog and difficulty concentrating (B12, B1), tingling or numbness in hands and feet (B12, B6), cracked lips and mouth sores (B2, B6), hair loss and brittle nails (B7/biotin), irritability and mood disturbances (B6, B12, folate), pale or yellowish skin (B12, folate), and weakened immune function (B6, B12). Vegans are at high risk for B12 deficiency. Alcoholics are at risk for B1 (thiamine) deficiency. Women of childbearing age need adequate folate for neural tube defect prevention.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take B complex gummies every day?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. B vitamins are water-soluble, meaning excess amounts are excreted through urine rather than accumulating in body tissue like fat-soluble vitamins. Daily supplementation is safe and recommended for consistent benefit. The only B vitamin with a known toxicity risk at high doses is B6 (pyridoxine), which can cause peripheral neuropathy (nerve damage) at chronic doses exceeding 100mg per day — well above the amounts found in B complex gummies. B3 (niacin) can cause flushing at high doses, but most gummies use niacinamide, which does not cause flushing.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When is the best time to take B complex gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Take B complex gummies in the morning or early afternoon with food. B vitamins support energy metabolism and can mildly stimulate alertness, so taking them in the evening may affect sleep onset in some individuals. Taking with food improves absorption and reduces the mild nausea that some people experience with B vitamins on an empty stomach. Consistency of daily timing matters more than the exact hour — choose a time you can maintain as a habit, such as with breakfast.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Who needs a B complex supplement?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Groups at highest risk for B vitamin deficiency and who benefit most from supplementation include: vegans and vegetarians (B12 is found only in animal products), adults over 50 (reduced B12 absorption with age), pregnant and breastfeeding women (increased folate and B12 needs), people who consume alcohol regularly (depletes B1, B6, folate), those taking certain medications (metformin depletes B12, oral contraceptives deplete B6 and folate), individuals with inflammatory bowel disease (impaired B vitamin absorption), and anyone experiencing chronic fatigue, brain fog, or mood disturbances that may indicate subclinical deficiency.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why does my urine turn bright yellow after taking B complex?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Bright yellow urine after taking B complex supplements is caused by riboflavin (vitamin B2) excretion. B2 is a naturally bright yellow pigment, and because it is water-soluble, excess amounts beyond what your body needs are excreted through the kidneys, turning urine a vivid yellow color. This is completely harmless and actually indicates that your kidneys are functioning properly by filtering excess water-soluble vitamins. It is not a sign of overdose or waste — your body absorbs what it needs and efficiently eliminates the surplus.' },
    },
  ],
};
