    <h2 id="why-b-complex">Why You Need All 8 B Vitamins Working Together</h2>

    <p>The 8 B vitamins function as a coordinated system — each one plays a unique biochemical role, but they work synergistically to power energy metabolism, maintain nervous system function, support DNA synthesis, and regulate mood. Supplementing individual B vitamins in isolation can actually create imbalances; for example, high-dose B12 without adequate folate can mask a folate deficiency, and high-dose B6 without B12 may not address the underlying neurological symptoms. A complete B complex ensures all 8 vitamins are present in balanced proportions to support the entire metabolic pathway.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">40%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans are estimated to have suboptimal B vitamin levels. Vitamin B12 deficiency affects <strong>up to 15% of the general population and 20% of adults over 60</strong>, while 30-40% of people carry the MTHFR gene variant that impairs folate metabolism. A B complex supplement with methylated forms addresses both issues simultaneously.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The critical differentiator between B complex supplements is the vitamin forms used. Cheap B complex products use synthetic forms — folic acid (instead of methylfolate), cyanocobalamin (instead of methylcobalamin) — that require enzymatic conversion in the body. For the 30-40% of the population with MTHFR variants, synthetic folic acid provides minimal benefit. Premium B complex products use methylated, bioactive forms that work for everyone regardless of genetic variations. This distinction is the single most important factor in choosing a B complex supplement.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
