        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Energy Metabolism (B1, B2, B3, B5)</strong>
        <p>These four B vitamins are direct cofactors in the citric acid cycle and electron transport chain — the biochemical pathways that convert carbohydrates, fats, and proteins into ATP (cellular energy). Deficiency in any one impairs the entire energy production process, causing fatigue.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Brain & Nerve Function (B6, B12, Folate)</strong>
        <p>B6 is essential for neurotransmitter synthesis (serotonin, dopamine, GABA). B12 maintains the myelin sheath that insulates nerve fibers. Folate supports brain cell development and homocysteine metabolism — elevated homocysteine is linked to cognitive decline and dementia risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="dna" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>DNA Synthesis (B9/Folate, B12)</strong>
        <p>Folate and B12 are essential for DNA synthesis and cell division. Folate deficiency during pregnancy causes neural tube defects. In adults, these vitamins support red blood cell production — deficiency causes megaloblastic anemia with oversized, dysfunctional red blood cells.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sparkle" size={22} /></div>
