    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin B Complex Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the 8 B vitamins in a B complex?</summary>
      <p>B1 (thiamine), B2 (riboflavin), B3 (niacin), B5 (pantothenic acid), B6 (pyridoxine), B7 (biotin), B9 (folate), and B12 (cobalamin). Each plays a unique role in energy metabolism, brain function, DNA synthesis, and cellular health. They work synergistically — supplementing all 8 together ensures balanced function.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why are methylated B vitamins better?</summary>
      <p>Methylated forms (methylfolate, methylcobalamin) are bioactive — your body uses them immediately without conversion. 30-40% of people carry MTHFR variants that impair conversion of synthetic folic acid. Methylated forms work for everyone regardless of genetics.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are signs of B vitamin deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Persistent fatigue, brain fog, tingling in hands/feet, cracked lips, hair loss, irritability, pale skin, and weakened immunity. Vegans risk B12 deficiency. Alcoholics risk B1 deficiency. Women of childbearing age need adequate folate.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take B complex gummies every day?</summary>
      <p>Yes. B vitamins are water-soluble — excess is excreted in urine, not stored in tissue. Daily use is safe. The only toxicity risk is B6 above 100mg/day chronically (nerve damage). Gummy doses (2-25mg B6) are safe.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take B complex gummies?</summary>
      <p>Morning or early afternoon with food. B vitamins support energy metabolism and can mildly stimulate alertness, potentially affecting sleep if taken in the evening. Take with food to improve absorption and reduce nausea.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Who needs a B complex supplement?</summary>
      <p>Vegans (B12), adults over 50 (reduced B12 absorption), pregnant women (folate), alcohol consumers (B1, B6, folate), metformin users (B12), oral contraceptive users (B6, folate), IBD patients, and anyone with chronic fatigue or brain fog.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why does my urine turn bright yellow?</summary>
      <p>Riboflavin (B2) is a bright yellow pigment. Excess B2 is excreted through urine, causing the vivid color. This is completely harmless and indicates healthy kidney function filtering excess water-soluble vitamins.</p>
    </details>

